"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087551","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-03-26","<p>As set out in the methodology, the heat source is designed to replicate a heat flux which is representative of a fully developed, post flash-over compartment fire. This would be more severe than is used in most standard classification tests but similar to the severity of a BS 8414 large scale test.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087551/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-26T15:14:03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087551/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087551/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-03-12","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, following the publication of the Buildings Research Establishment interim report, Fire performance of cladding materials research - experimental methodology and performance criteria, what assessmentÂ they have made of the temperature needed to test the panels to ensure their performance reflects that experienced of a real fire in a cladding system on a high-rise residential building.","false","Biography information for Lord Porter of Spalding",,"Lord Porter of Spalding","HL14471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087553","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-03-26","<p>The Association of Composite Door Manufacturers (ACDM) have committed to taking action to repair and replace affected fire doors where required. The ACDM are leading on producing the industry-led remediation plan. It is for them to engage with stakeholders and bring forward their proposal.</p><p>As part of our investigation into the fire door industry, my department continues to work with test establishments and other stakeholders to raise quality and standards across the market.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087553/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-26T15:15:55.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087553/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087553/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-03-12","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what discussions they have had with the test establishments that tested glass reinforced plastic composite fire doors about contributing to the remediation plan for replacing non-compliant fire doors being developed by the Association of Composite Door Manufacturers.","false","Biography information for Lord Porter of Spalding",,"Lord Porter of Spalding","HL14472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087554","Home Office","false","2019-03-26","<p>Population projections, including for different migration scenarios, are the responsibility of the independent Office for National Statistics.</p><p>The Home Office does not publish the projections indicated. As indicated in the report for the Migration Advisory Committee (MAC), Evaluation of existing migration forecasting methods and models, there are many social, economic and political drivers which can impact migration flows, making forecasting migration an extremely difficult task. Migration is susceptible to shock events which are, by their very nature, hard to predict, such as economic cycles, military conflict and policy changes. Therefore, the probability of a single forecast being correct is low.</p><p>Notwithstanding this, we remain on track to deliver our commitment of resettling up to 23,000 vulnerable refugees under our resettlement schemes by 2020 and are confident that the outcome of EU Exit will not impact our ability to achieve this.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087554/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-26T16:18:50.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087554/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087554/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-12","Asylum","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is their projected forecast for the number of (1) refugees, and (2) asylum seekers they expect to accept in each of the next five years; and whether they expect those projected figures to change if the UK (a) does, and (b) does not, leave the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL14473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087555","Home Office","false","2019-03-26","<p>The rights of people granted refugee status in the UK are unchanged when we leave the EU. The UK will continue to be bound by the 1951 UN Refugee Convention and the European Convention on Human Rights and will continue to provide protection to all those who need it in accordance with our international obligations.</p><p>Regardless of how the UK exits the EU, the rights and status of those who have been granted refugee status in the UK will remain unchanged, as the 1951 UN Refugee Convention is not contingent on EU membership.</p><p>The Government continues to work closely with relevant partners such as the UNHCR and the International Organization for Migration (IOM) to ensure the UK continues to meet our international obligations, and to facilitate the safe transfer of children under family reunification.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087555/answer",,,,,"HL14476 ; HL14477","2019-03-26T16:15:50.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087555/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087555/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-12","Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether refugees will be afforded the same rights as now if the UK withdraws from the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL14474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087556","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-03-25","<p>We have committed to introduce legislation to bring non-asylum immigration matters into the scope of legal aid for separated migrant children.</p><p>Legal aid for family reunion may be available under the Exceptional Case Funding (ECF) scheme, where there is a breach or risk of breach of ECHR rights, and subject to means and merits tests. We recently committed to work with legal practitioners to review and simplify the ECF application forms and guidance and ensure that funding is provided in as timely a manner as possible.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087556/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-25T17:21:21.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087556/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087556/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-03-12","Legal Aid Scheme: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have any plans to reintroduce legal aid for refugee family reunion; and if not, why not.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL14475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087557","Home Office","false","2019-03-26","<p>The rights of people granted refugee status in the UK are unchanged when we leave the EU. The UK will continue to be bound by the 1951 UN Refugee Convention and the European Convention on Human Rights and will continue to provide protection to all those who need it in accordance with our international obligations.</p><p>Regardless of how the UK exits the EU, the rights and status of those who have been granted refugee status in the UK will remain unchanged, as the 1951 UN Refugee Convention is not contingent on EU membership.</p><p>The Government continues to work closely with relevant partners such as the UNHCR and the International Organization for Migration (IOM) to ensure the UK continues to meet our international obligations, and to facilitate the safe transfer of children under family reunification.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087557/answer",,,,,"HL14474 ; HL14477","2019-03-26T16:15:50.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087557/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087557/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-12","Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what contingency plans are in place for refugees in anticipation of the UK withdrawing from the EU without a deal.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL14476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087559","Home Office","false","2019-03-26","<p>The rights of people granted refugee status in the UK are unchanged when we leave the EU. The UK will continue to be bound by the 1951 UN Refugee Convention and the European Convention on Human Rights and will continue to provide protection to all those who need it in accordance with our international obligations.</p><p>Regardless of how the UK exits the EU, the rights and status of those who have been granted refugee status in the UK will remain unchanged, as the 1951 UN Refugee Convention is not contingent on EU membership.</p><p>The Government continues to work closely with relevant partners such as the UNHCR and the International Organization for Migration (IOM) to ensure the UK continues to meet our international obligations, and to facilitate the safe transfer of children under family reunification.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087559/answer",,,,,"HL14474 ; HL14476","2019-03-26T16:15:50.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087559/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087559/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-12","Asylum","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have acted upon advice from humanitarian organisations regarding the protection of refugees and asylum seekers after the UK has withdrawn from the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL14477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087560","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-03-19","<p>In the recently published Clean Air Strategy we committed to set a new, ambitious, long term target for PM<sub>2.5 </sub>as well as to publish evidence early in 2019 to examine what action would be needed to meet the World Health Organizationâs annual mean guideline limit of 10 Âµg/m<sup>3</sup>. That work is ongoing and will be published in due course.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087560/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-19T12:25:47.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087560/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087560/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-03-12","Air Pollution","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what considerationÂ they have given to setting legally binding targets to meet WHO-recommended limit values for particulate matter across the UK, and if consideration has been given, when the targetsÂ will be implemented.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of St Albans",,"The Lord Bishop of St Albans","HL14478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087561","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-03-25","<p>All measures which reduce air pollution will reduce exposure of children to harmful pollutants. Our Clean Air Strategy is clear that children are impacted by air pollution more than the general population, and all the measures set out in the Strategy will reduce emissions of pollution, improving public health.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has put in place a Â£3.5 billion plan to improve air quality and reduce harmful emissions, which includes Â£495 million for councils to improve air quality. Councils with serious air quality problems may bid for a share of these funds.</p><p> </p><p>Local authorities are best placed to target action to improve local air quality. Defraâs Air Quality Grant Programme provides funding to local authorities for projects in local communities to tackle air pollution and reduce emissions which may include action targeting schools. Defra has awarded over Â£57 million in funding since the air quality grant started in 1997. A further Â£3 million has been allocated for 2018/19.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087561/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-25T17:49:32.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087561/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087561/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-03-12","Air Pollution: Children and Young People","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what consideration has been given to establishing a ring-fenced fund to protect children and young people from toxic air.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of St Albans",,"The Lord Bishop of St Albans","HL14479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087562","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-03-26","<p>In January, the Government launched the Clean Air Strategy, our world leading plan which focuses on tackling air pollution in England. Air pollution is the top environmental risk to human health in the UK. The Strategy, jointly launched by the Secretaries of State for Environment and Health, was welcomed by the World Health Organization as âan example for the rest of the world to follow.â</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>All the measures set out will reduce emissions of pollution, improving public health. The Strategy includes the comprehensive action required across all parts of the Government to improve air quality for everyone, including children and young people.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Ministers and officials across Government Departments will continue to regularly discuss air pollution and how to reduce it so we can improve the air we breathe now and for future generations.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087562/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-26T16:17:32.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087562/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087562/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-03-12","Air Pollution: Children and Young People","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what consideration has been given to developing a cross-governmental healthy air for children action plan as part of a national framework to protect children and young people from toxic air.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of St Albans",,"The Lord Bishop of St Albans","HL14480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087563","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-26","<p>The Department of Health and Social Care is currently liaising closely with the Department for Work and Pensions, NHS England and the NHS Business Service Authority on this important issue, and reviewing all available evidence.</p><p>As part of this work, the Government is carefully considering how to proceed with regard to individuals who were placed on contributory, rather than income-related, Employment and Support Allowance.</p>",,"Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087563/answer",,,,,"HL14484","2019-03-26T17:51:11.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087563/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087563/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-12","Prescriptions: Employment and Support Allowance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the number of individuals who were identified as entitled to income-related Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) but who were moved to contributory-based ESA from Incapacity Benefit who were eligible for free prescriptions that they were then unable to claim as a result of that move; and what plans they have to compensate those individuals for any prescription charge paid.","false","Biography information for Baroness Sherlock",,"Baroness Sherlock","HL14481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087564","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-26","<p>The Department of Health and Social Care is currently liaising closely with the Department for Work and Pensions, NHS England and the NHS Business Service Authority on this important issue, and reviewing all available evidence.</p><p>As part of this work, the Government is carefully considering how to proceed with regard to individuals who were placed on contributory, rather than income-related, Employment and Support Allowance.</p>",,"Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087564/answer",,,,,"HL14483","2019-03-26T17:51:32.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087564/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087564/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-12","Dental Services: Employment and Support Allowance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the number of individuals who were identified as entitled to income-related Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) but who were moved to contributory-based ESA from Incapacity Benefit who were eligible for freeÂ dental treatment and denturesÂ that they were then unable to claim as a result of that move; and what plans they have to compensate those individuals for any charges paid for such treatment.","false","Biography information for Baroness Sherlock",,"Baroness Sherlock","HL14482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087566","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-26","<p>The Department of Health and Social Care is currently liaising closely with the Department for Work and Pensions, NHS England and the NHS Business Service Authority on this important issue, and reviewing all available evidence.</p><p>As part of this work, the Government is carefully considering how to proceed with regard to individuals who were placed on contributory, rather than income-related, Employment and Support Allowance.</p>",,"Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087566/answer",,,,,"HL14482","2019-03-26T17:51:32.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087566/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087566/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-12","Ophthalmic Services: Employment and Support Allowance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the number of individuals who were identified as entitled to income-related Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) but who were moved to contributory-based ESA from Incapacity Benefit who were eligible for freeÂ sight tests and glasses that they were then unable to claim as a result of that move; and what plans they have to compensate those individuals for any charges paid for such sight tests and glasses.","false","Biography information for Baroness Sherlock",,"Baroness Sherlock","HL14483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087567","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-26","<p>The Department of Health and Social Care is currently liaising closely with the Department for Work and Pensions, NHS England and the NHS Business Service Authority on this important issue, and reviewing all available evidence.</p><p>As part of this work, the Government is carefully considering how to proceed with regard to individuals who were placed on contributory, rather than income-related, Employment and Support Allowance.</p>",,"Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087567/answer",,,,,"HL14481","2019-03-26T17:51:11.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087567/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087567/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-12","Prescriptions: Employment and Support Allowance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the number of individuals who were identified as entitled to income-related Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) but who were moved to contributory-based ESA from Incapacity Benefit who were eligible for freeÂ wigs and fabric supports that they were then unable to claim as a result of that move; and what plans they have to compensate those individuals for any charges paid for such wigs and fabric supports.","false","Biography information for Baroness Sherlock",,"Baroness Sherlock","HL14484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087568","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-26","<p>The Department of Health and Social Care is currently liaising closely with the Department for Work and Pensions, NHS England and the NHS Business Service Authority on this important issue, and reviewing all available evidence.</p><p>As part of this work, the Government is carefully considering how to proceed with regard to individuals who were placed on contributory, rather than income-related, Employment and Support Allowance.</p>",,"Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087568/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-26T17:51:52.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087568/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087568/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-12","Out-patients: Travel","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the number of individuals who were identified as entitled to income-related Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) but who were moved to contributory-based ESA from Incapacity Benefit who were eligible forÂ financial assistance with travel fares to attend hospitals or other establishments for NHS treatment or servicesÂ that they were then unable to claim as a result of that move; and what plans they have to compensate those individuals for any charges paid for such travel fares.","false","Biography information for Baroness Sherlock",,"Baroness Sherlock","HL14485"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087569","Department for Education","false","2019-03-22","<p>We are working closely with officials at the Department for Work and Pensions and other government departments to understand the impact of the Employment and Support Allowance legal entitlements and administrative practice exercise and any potential issues arising from it.</p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087569/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-22T14:57:20.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087569/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087569/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-03-12","Free School Meals: Employment and Support Allowance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the number of individuals who were identified as entitled to income-related Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) but who were moved to contributory-based ESA from Incapacity Benefit who were eligible for freeÂ school mealsÂ that they were then unable to claim as a result of that move; and what plans they have to compensate those individuals for any charges paid for such meals.","false","Biography information for Baroness Sherlock",,"Baroness Sherlock","HL14486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087570","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-03-26","<p>Her Majestyâs Government considers evidence of the effectiveness of all consumer legislation periodically and will take action where appropriate.</p><p> </p><p>In April 2018, the Government published a Consumer Green Paper consulting on a variety of issues including seeking views on the legal framework covering consumer to consumer transactions, which would include new and used goods. The Consumer Green Paper is available in the Libraries of the House. We will publish a Consumer White Paper in due course.</p>",,"Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087570/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-26T16:52:13.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087570/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087570/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-03-12","Home Shopping","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the effectiveness of consumer protection legislation governing the sale of both new and used private goodsÂ online.","false","Biography information for Lord Shipley",,"Lord Shipley","HL14487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087572","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-03-25","<p>The Electrical Equipment (Safety) Regulations 2016 places duties on manufacturers, importers and distributors of electrical equipment to ensure that where a safety issue is identified, appropriate action is taken to withdraw, recall or otherwise bring the equipment into conformity. Distributors, including retailers of second-hand goods, also have a duty to act with care to ensure that any products they sell meet the legal safety requirements. There are no plans to introduce any further legislation.</p><p> </p><p>The Office for Product Safety and Standards operates an incident management procedure for managing consumer product safety incidents, to deliver on its wider purpose of protecting consumers and building public confidence in the product safety system. It also makes available information on recalled electrical products through its dedicated product recall website.</p>",,"Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087572/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-25T11:55:52.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087572/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087572/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-03-12","Consumer Goods: Electrical Safety","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the effectiveness of legislation governing the sale of recalled electrical products; and whether they have any plans to introduce legislation covering the sale of such products.","false","Biography information for Lord Shipley",,"Lord Shipley","HL14488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087573","Home Office","false","2019-03-26","<p>In accordance with arrangements introduced in 2016, relevant medical information is requested from the GPs of those who apply for a firearms licence before the licence is issued. Police forces must be satisfied that a person does not pose a danger to public safety before granting or renewing a firearm licence and they may require sight of medical information before proceeding to issue the licence.</p><p>The Government does not collect statistics on the participation of GPs in the firearms licensing process, placing of the encoded reminder, or the level of any fee that GPs may charge their patients for providing medical information to the police. However, we do understand from information from informal reports from police forces and firearms licence applicants that participation rates amongst GPs and the fees that they charge are variable. We have been in discussions with the police, medical bodies and shooting representatives about improving the arrangements for providing medical evidence and how greater consistency can be achieved.</p><p>The Policing and Crime Act 2017 introduced a power to enable the Secretary of State to issue statutory guidance to the police on their firearms licensing functions, which include the medical arrangements. Before issuing the statutory guidance, the Secretary of State must consult the National Police Chiefâs Council and the Chief Constable of the Police Service of Scotland, and we will also consult publicly on the guidance before it is published. Once issued, the police will be required to have regard to this guidance, and this will therefore help to ensure greater consistency in practice across the country. The Government intends to launch the consultation on the statutory guidance before the summer recess.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087573/answer",,,,,"HL14490 ; HL14491 ; HL14492","2019-03-26T16:51:22.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087573/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087573/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-12","Firearms: Licensing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the fees charged by GPs to provide medical information to support a firearms licence application.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Shrewsbury",,"The Earl of Shrewsbury","HL14489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087574","Home Office","false","2019-03-26","<p>In accordance with arrangements introduced in 2016, relevant medical information is requested from the GPs of those who apply for a firearms licence before the licence is issued. Police forces must be satisfied that a person does not pose a danger to public safety before granting or renewing a firearm licence and they may require sight of medical information before proceeding to issue the licence.</p><p>The Government does not collect statistics on the participation of GPs in the firearms licensing process, placing of the encoded reminder, or the level of any fee that GPs may charge their patients for providing medical information to the police. However, we do understand from information from informal reports from police forces and firearms licence applicants that participation rates amongst GPs and the fees that they charge are variable. We have been in discussions with the police, medical bodies and shooting representatives about improving the arrangements for providing medical evidence and how greater consistency can be achieved.</p><p>The Policing and Crime Act 2017 introduced a power to enable the Secretary of State to issue statutory guidance to the police on their firearms licensing functions, which include the medical arrangements. Before issuing the statutory guidance, the Secretary of State must consult the National Police Chiefâs Council and the Chief Constable of the Police Service of Scotland, and we will also consult publicly on the guidance before it is published. Once issued, the police will be required to have regard to this guidance, and this will therefore help to ensure greater consistency in practice across the country. The Government intends to launch the consultation on the statutory guidance before the summer recess.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087574/answer",,,,,"HL14489 ; HL14491 ; HL14492","2019-03-26T16:51:22.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087574/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1087574/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-12","Firearms: Licensing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the number of encoded reminders that have been placed on the patient records of firearms licence applicants following the grant or renewal of a firearms licence.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Shrewsbury",,"The Earl of Shrewsbury","HL14490"
