"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086547","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-03-14","<p>The Government is committed to leaseholders receiving fair and transparent charges. For this reason, we asked Lord Best and his Property Agent Working Group to consider leasehold service charges. This includes reviewing the standards around the transparency of service charges and other fees and charges, how they are presented to consumers and putting them into a statutory code for managing agents, which will be beneficial to all leaseholders. We expect to receive the Working Group's recommendations this summer and we will respond with our plans later this year.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086547/answer",,,,,"230678","2019-03-14T14:12:45.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086547/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086547/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-03-11","Leasehold: Unfair Practices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, when he plans to bring forward legislative proposals on tackling excessive charges levied on the owners of leasehold homes.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","230677"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086548","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-03-14","<p>The Government is committed to leaseholders receiving fair and transparent charges. For this reason, we asked Lord Best and his Property Agent Working Group to consider leasehold service charges. This includes reviewing the standards around the transparency of service charges and other fees and charges, how they are presented to consumers and putting them into a statutory code for managing agents, which will be beneficial to all leaseholders. We expect to receive the Working Group's recommendations this summer and we will respond with our plans later this year.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086548/answer",,,,,"230677","2019-03-14T14:12:45.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086548/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086548/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-03-11","Leasehold: Unfair Practices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether the legislation he plans to bring forward to tackle excessive charges levied on leaseholders will apply to existing arrangements or only to new homes completed after the legislation comes into force.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","230678"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086549","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-03-14","<p>The Government has committed to ensuring that freeholders who pay charges for the maintenance of communal areas and facilities on a private or mixed tenure estate can access equivalent rights as leaseholders to challenge their reasonableness. In addition, we have committed to protecting leaseholders who are suffering at the hands of rogue managing agents every day from unexpected costs or excessive fees for poor quality repairs.</p><p>We intend to create a new statutory regime for freeholders based on the leaseholder rights contained in the Landlord and Tenant Act 1985. This will ensure maintenance charges must be reasonably incurred and services provided are of an acceptable standard. We will provide freeholders with the ability to challenge the reasonableness of the charges they are required to pay towards the maintenance of communal areas and facilities at the First-tier Tribunal. We are also considering whether freeholders should have a right to change the provider of maintenance services by applying to the tribunal for the appointment of a new manager. We will bring forward legislation as soon as Parliamentary time allows.</p><p>We have asked Lord Best to chair a working group to look at regulating and professionalising property agents. This includes reviewing the standards around the transparency of service charges and other fees and charges, how they are presented to consumers and putting them into a statutory code for managing agents. Lord Bestâs working group will report back to Ministers later this summer.</p><p>We are also looking at the future use of charges and restrictions beyond service charges â such as permission fees, administration charges and other restrictions and covenants faced by leaseholders and resident freeholders, and consider whether they should be capped or banned. We will consider this alongside Lord Bests proposals.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086549/answer",,,,,"230675 ; 230676","2019-03-14T14:17:06.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086549/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086549/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-03-11","Housing Estates: Unfair Practices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether he has plans to introduce legislative proposals to replicate the provisions of the Freehold Properties (Management Charges and Shared Facilities) Bill 2017-19 introduced by the Hon Member for Bishop Auckland.","false","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","Chipping Barnet","Theresa Villiers","230679"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086550","Department for Transport","false","2019-03-14","<p>The agreements with both Freight Operators are still live, and as a responsible Government we have a duty to prepare for all scenarios. In the event that a deal is implemented the Department will review its options and exercise its rights where appropriate, noting that the amount retained will be dependent on the specific scenario at the time.</p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086550/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T11:14:15.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086550/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086550/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-03-11","Brittany Ferries and DFDS","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Written Statement of 7 January 2019, Haulage Update, HCWS 1233, how much and what proportion of the monies awarded to (a) Brittany Ferries and (b) DFDS for the contingency transport provisions outlined in that Written Statement will be retained by the public purse in the event that the UK agrees a withdrawal agreement with the EU.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","230779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086551","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-03-19","<p>No instructions have been issued. The UK Government is considering the details of the Advisory Opinion carefully.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086551/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-19T16:49:48.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086551/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086551/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-11","British Indian Ocean Territory: Sovereignty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what instructions he has issued to the Commissioner of the British Indian Ocean Territory on the advisory opinion of the International Court of Justice of 25 February 2019.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","230780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086552","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-19","<p>NHS England has made no assessment of the effectiveness of clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) in commissioning therapeutic care for survivors of sexual assault.</p><p> </p><p>Following publication of the Strategic Direction for Sexual Assault and Abuse Services in April 2018, and the NHS Long Term Plan in January 2019, a letter was sent to commissioners on 6 February from myself and Kate Davies, Director of Health and Justice, Armed Forces and Sexual Assault Services Commissioning at NHS England. The letter asks commissioners to look at how they are meeting their responsibilities for victims and survivors of sexual assault and sets out the importance of commissioning better services that support victims in an informed and consistent way.</p><p> </p><p>A copy of the letter can be found at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/services-for-victims-of-sexual-assault-letter-to-nhs-commissioners" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/services-for-victims-of-sexual-assault-letter-to-nhs-commissioners</a></p><p> </p><p>Information on the proportion of their budget CCGs have spent on therapeutic services for survivors of sexual abuse is not collected or held centrally.</p><p> </p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086552/answer",,,,,"230782","2019-03-19T17:52:33.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086552/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086552/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-11","Sexual Offences: Victim Support Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of CCGs in commissioning therapeutic services for survivors of sexual abuse.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","230781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086553","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-19","<p>NHS England has made no assessment of the effectiveness of clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) in commissioning therapeutic care for survivors of sexual assault.</p><p> </p><p>Following publication of the Strategic Direction for Sexual Assault and Abuse Services in April 2018, and the NHS Long Term Plan in January 2019, a letter was sent to commissioners on 6 February from myself and Kate Davies, Director of Health and Justice, Armed Forces and Sexual Assault Services Commissioning at NHS England. The letter asks commissioners to look at how they are meeting their responsibilities for victims and survivors of sexual assault and sets out the importance of commissioning better services that support victims in an informed and consistent way.</p><p> </p><p>A copy of the letter can be found at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/services-for-victims-of-sexual-assault-letter-to-nhs-commissioners" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/services-for-victims-of-sexual-assault-letter-to-nhs-commissioners</a></p><p> </p><p>Information on the proportion of their budget CCGs have spent on therapeutic services for survivors of sexual abuse is not collected or held centrally.</p><p> </p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086553/answer",,,,,"230781","2019-03-19T17:52:33.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086553/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086553/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-11","Sexual Offences: Victim Support Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what proportion of their budget CCGs have spent on therapeutic services for survivors of sexual abuse.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","230782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086554","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-03-19","<p>The Commissioner has issued no Ordinances in 2019 and currently has no plans for any additional legislation following the February 2019 Advisory Opinion of the International Court of Justice.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086554/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-19T16:52:28.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086554/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086554/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-11","British Indian Ocean Territory: Sovereignty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what ordinances the Commissioner for the British Indian Ocean Territory has issued in 2019; and what additional legislative proposals are planned following the February 2019 advisory opinion of the International Court of Justice.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","230783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086555","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-03-19","<p>The UK consistently reiterates its willingness to discuss scientific work in the British Indian Ocean Territory (BIOT) with Mauritius. The BIOT Marine Protected Area (MPA) is highly valued by scientists from many countries who consider it a global reference site for marine conservation in an ocean which is heavily overfished. Ministers are committed to further consultation with Mauritius about the establishment of the MPA in order to have due regard to its rights and interests, as directed by the Arbitral Tribunal of the UN Convention on the Law of the Sea. Implementation of the Tribunalâs Award started with a series of bilateral talks, the latest of which took place in August 2016.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086555/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-19T16:53:41.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086555/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086555/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-11","British Indian Ocean Territory: Mauritius","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he plans to have discussions with his counterpart in Mauritius before a decision is made on scientific work in the (a) Chagos Islands and (c) exclusive economic zone declared by Mauritius around those islands.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","230784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086556","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-03-19","<p>Two officials from the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) and an official from the British Indian Ocean Territory (BIOT) Administration have already visited BIOT this year. There are tentative plans for the British Indian Ocean Territory Commissioner and Deputy Commissioner to visit BIOT in May and for other FCO and BIOT Administration officials to visit during the course of the year.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086556/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-19T16:54:32.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086556/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086556/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-11","British Indian Ocean Territory: Visits Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what plans the (a) British Indian Ocean Territory Commissioner and (b) his staff have to visit the Chagos Archipelago in 2019.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","230785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086557","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-03-19","<p>The Commissioner has made no disposal of land under section 14 of the British Indian Ocean Territory Constitution Order 2004.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086557/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-19T16:56:26.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086557/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086557/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-11","British Indian Ocean Territory: Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he has made any disposals of land under section 14 of the British Indian Ocean Territory (Constitution) Order 2004.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","230786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086558","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-03-19","<p>Before making a decision on the disposal of land under section 14 of the British Indian Ocean Territory (Constitution) Order 20014, the Commissioner would be obliged to:</p><ul><li>Consider and comply with any law for the time being in force in the Territory. This would include the Acquisition of Land for Public Purposes Ordinance 1983, which confirms and declares that all land in the Territory is Crown Land. Before any disposition of land could lawfully be made, this Ordinance would require amendment or repeal. Such amendment or repeal would be subject to the disallowance procedure provided by section 11 of the Order;</li><li>Confirm and comply with any instructions provided by a Secretary of State; and</li><li>Ensure that any disposition of land could otherwise lawfully be granted in accordance with the Order.</li></ul>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086558/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-19T16:57:27.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086558/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086558/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-11","British Indian Ocean Territory: Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what criteria he has to assess before making a decision on the disposal of land under section 14 of the British Indian Ocean Territory (Constitution) Order 2004.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","230787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086559","Department for Education","false","2019-03-14","<p>The following table provides the full-time equivalent (FTE) number of teaching assistants in state funded nursery and primary schools in West Yorkshire and England in each November, from 2011 to 2017.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>West Yorkshire</p></td><td><p>England</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011[1]</p></td><td><p>7,439</p></td><td><p>136,876</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012[2]</p></td><td><p>7,725</p></td><td><p>146,660</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013[3]</p></td><td><p>8,237</p></td><td><p>156,238</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>8,399</p></td><td><p>166,230</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015[4]</p></td><td><p>9,043</p></td><td><p>174,533</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016[5]</p></td><td><p>9,125</p></td><td><p>177,692</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>8,972</p></td><td><p>176,242</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: School Workforce Census</p><p>West Yorkshire includes Bradford, Calderdale, Kirklees, Leeds and Wakefield local authorities. Comparable information for 2010 is not available.</p><p>[1] 2011 figures for West Yorkshire exclude 14 out of 735 nursery and primary schools that did not provide a return for teaching assistant numbers.</p><p>[2] 2012 figures for West Yorkshire exclude 10 out of 734 nursery and primary schools that did not provide a return for teaching assistant numbers.</p><p>[3] 2013 figures for West Yorkshire exclude 5 out of 734 nursery and primary schools that did not provide a return for teaching assistant numbers.</p><p>[4] 2015 figures for West Yorkshire exclude 1 out of 729 nursery and primary schools that did not provide a return for teaching assistant numbers.</p><p>[5] 2016 figures for West Yorkshire exclude 5 out of 728 nursery and primary schools that did not provide a return for teaching assistant numbers.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086559/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T17:34:46.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086559/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086559/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-03-11","Classroom Assistants: West Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many teaching assistants have been employed in primary schools in West Yorkshire in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","230863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086560","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-03-15","<p>The Government does not monitor the decisions made by local authorities on planning applications. Planning applications must be determined in accordance with the development plan unless material considerations, including national planning policy, indicate otherwise. This means that the best way for local authorities to prevent the success of speculative applications is to have an up-to-date development plan and maintain a five year land supply of deliverable sites for housing.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086560/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-15T14:26:45.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086560/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086560/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-03-11","Local Government: Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the effect of maintaining a five-year land supply on the ability of local authorities to reject planning applications.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","230864"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086561","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-03-19","<p>The Government is committed to reducing homelessness and rough sleeping. No one should ever have to sleep rough. That is why this summer we published the cross-government Rough Sleeping Strategy. This sets out an ambitious Â£100 million package to help people who sleep rough now, but also puts in place the structures that will end rough sleeping once and for all. Already, this has provided over 1,750 new bed spaces and 500 staffâ this means there are more people in warm beds tonight as direct result of government funding. In all, the Government has now committed over Â£1.2 billion to tackle homelessness and rough sleeping over the spending review period.</p><p>The Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government does not collect information on the number of homeless veterans in Yorkshire and Humber.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086561/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-19T17:28:50.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086561/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086561/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-03-11","Homelessness: Veterans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the number of homeless veterans in Yorkshire and the Humber in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","230865"
