"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086580","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-03-20","<p>There are a range of options for replacing this capacity over the coming decades. This Government remains committed to delivering secure, low cost electricity to consumers. We agreed to the first new nuclear power station in a generation at Hinkley Point C, which will provide 3.2 gigawatts of secure, low carbon electricity for at least 60 years and power nearly 6 million homes. We also procured over 3GW of offshore wind in a single Contract for Difference auction in our 2017 auction â at a price of Â£57.50 per megawatt hour.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086580/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-20T11:25:32.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086580/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086580/answer","Watford","Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086580/answer/previousversion/107886","Biography information for Richard Harrington","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-03-11","Hinkley Point B Power Station: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 1 March 2019 to Question 226169 on Hinkley Point B Power Station: Closures, what plans the Government has to replace the 965 megawatts generation capacity of Hinkley Point B; and what the timescales are for implementing the replacement of that capacity.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","230793"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086581","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-03-20","<p>There are a range of options for replacing this capacity over the coming decades. This Government remains committed to delivering secure, low cost electricity to consumers through a diverse energy mix including renewables and nuclear new build. We agreed to the first new nuclear power station in a generation at Hinkley Point C, which will provide 3.2 gigawatts of secure, low carbon electricity for at least 60 years and power nearly 6 million homes.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086581/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-20T11:24:14.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086581/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086581/answer","Watford","Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086581/answer/previousversion/107887","Biography information for Richard Harrington","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-03-11","Hartlepool Power Station: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 1 March 2019 to Question 226166 on Hartlepool Power Station: Closures, what plans the Government has to replace the 1185 MW generation capacity of Hartlepool; and what the timescales are for the replacement of that capacity.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","230794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086582","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-03-20","<p>There are a range of options for replacing this capacity over the coming decades. This Government remains committed to delivering secure, low cost electricity to consumers through a diverse energy mix including renewables and nuclear new build. We agreed to the first new nuclear power station in a generation at Hinkley Point C, which will provide 3.2 gigawatts of secure, low carbon electricity for at least 60 years and power nearly 6 million homes.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086582/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-20T11:26:32.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086582/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086582/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-03-11","Heysham 1 Power Station: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 1 March to Question 226167 on Heysham 1 Power Station: Closures, what plans the Government has to replace the 1155 megawatts generation capacity of Heysham 1; and what the timescales are for that replacement capacity.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","230795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086583","Department for Education","false","2019-03-19","<p>This is a matter for Her Majestyâs Chief Inspector, Amanda Spielman. I have asked her to write to the hon. Member and a copy of her reply will be placed in the Libraries of both Houses.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086583/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-19T15:45:13.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086583/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086583/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-03-11","John Roan School: Inspections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when Ofsted plans to carry out a monitoring inspection of the John Roan secondary school in the Royal Borough of Greenwich.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","230876"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086584","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-03-18","<p>The Secretary of State had no meetings with the Departmentâs Chief Scientific Adviser between 1 December 2018 and 28 February 2019; however, she did meet the Chief Scientific Adviser on 27<sup>th</sup> November 2018 as one of her first meetings in the Department. Baroness Buscombe meets with the Chief Scientific Adviser on a regular basis in her role as Minister in Charge of Research and Trialling.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086584/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-18T17:08:13.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086584/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086584/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-03-11","Department for Work and Pensions: Chief Scientific Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many meetings she had with her Departmentâs Chief Scientific Adviser between 1 December 2018 and 28 February 2019.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","230634"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086585","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-03-20","<p>The Government is supportive of developing the shale gas industry in the UK in a safe and sustainable way. It is not yet known how much of the UK shale gas resource will ultimately be recoverable, or what rates of extraction, deliverability or reliability could be assumed if shale sources are found to be viable. Therefore the likely impact on UK natural gas imports and exports is not yet known.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will continue to work with responsible companies prepared to invest in this industry as they proceed with the exploration process, to test the size and value of the potential reserves. We monitor the progress of the shale gas industry and will revise our estimates, as appropriate, as the industry develops.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086585/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-20T11:25:40.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086585/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086585/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-03-11","Fracking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether he has made an assessment of the implications for his policies of the March 2019 UK Onshore Oil and Gas report entitled Home grown UK shale gas: a bigger opportunity; and whether he has made an estimate of the date on which the UK will become a net exporter of gas.","false","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon","230606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086586","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-03-19","<p>The Governmentâs sport strategy, Sporting Future, encourages and promotes outdoor recreation. Use of our waterways by all can be a creative and fun way to engage with the natural world and to stay healthy.</p><p> </p><p>Sport England is actively engaged with British Canoeing and the Canal and River Trust to get more people from all backgrounds active. In addition Sport England is providing Â£6.85m to British Canoeing for the period between 2017 to 2021.</p><p> </p><p>The âpublic rights of navigationâ issue around access to waterways is dealt with by the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs and they are currently working with British Canoeing to consider solutions to access disputes.</p>","Eastleigh","Mims Davies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086586/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-19T11:24:36.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086586/answer","Biography information for Mims Davies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086586/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-03-11","Water Sports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the effect of current access rights to water on paddlesport participation in England.","false","Biography information for Ben Bradley","Mansfield","Ben Bradley","230877"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086587","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-03-14","<p>None of the Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sportâs suppliers have failed to meet the tax compliance criteria in the Procurement Policy Note 03/14.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086587/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T11:53:45.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086587/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086587/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-03-11","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to the guidance entitled, Procurement policy note 03/14: promoting tax compliance, how many suppliers were allocated contracts by his Department as a result of complying with (a) one and (b) more than one of the mitigating circumstances after failing the tax compliance questions.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","230878"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086588","Department for Transport","false","2019-03-13","<p>Nottinghamshire County Council, as local highway authority, is responsible for the maintenance and improvement of the local road network, including for the Mansfield constituency.</p><p> </p><p>The funding allocated to Nottinghamshire County Council by the Department for Transport from the Pothole Action Fund, since its inception, is shown in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Pothole Action Fund Â£m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>0.839</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017/18</p></td><td><p>1.989</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018/19</p></td><td><p>0.839</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>3.667</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086588/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-13T14:14:39.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086588/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086588/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-03-11","Roads: Nottinghamshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much funding has been allocated to (a) Mansfield and (b) Nottinghamshire from the Pothole Action Fund in each year since that fund's inception.","false","Biography information for Ben Bradley","Mansfield","Ben Bradley","230879"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086589","Department for International Development","false","2019-03-14","<p>All DFID contracts awarded in FY 17/18 and FY 18/19, suppliers were fully compliant with Procurement Policy Note 03/14: promoting tax compliance. Prior to 2017 such information was not centrally held.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086589/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T17:51:59.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086589/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086589/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-03-11","Department for International Development: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, with reference to the guidance entitled, Procurement policy note 03/14: promoting tax compliance, how many suppliers were allocated contracts by her Department as a result of complying with (a) one and (b) more than one of the mitigating circumstances after failing the tax compliance questions.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","230880"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086590","Women and Equalities","false","2019-03-15","<p>GEO have reviewed their relevant contracts and no contracts have been awarded to supplier in which the mitigating circumstances, with regards to tax compliance, apply.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086590/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-15T16:06:59.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086590/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086590/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2019-03-11","Government Equalities Office: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, with reference to the guidance entitled, Procurement policy note 03/14: promoting tax compliance, how many suppliers were allocated contracts by her Department as a result of complying with (a) one and (b) more than one of the mitigating circumstances after failing the tax compliance questions.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","230881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086591","Department for International Development","false","2019-03-14","<p>In FY 17/18 and FY 18/19, no suppliers were excluded from bidding for contracts due to failing to meet the criteria specified in Procurement Policy Note 03/14. Prior to 2017 such information was not centrally held.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086591/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T17:52:53.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086591/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086591/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-03-11","Department for International Development: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many suppliers were excluded from bidding for contracts due to failing the meet the criteria specified in Procurement Policy Note 03/14 by (a) Government Department and (b) year since 2014.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","230882"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086592","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-03-18","<p>Having taken over responsibility for this task in October 2018, the Rural Payments Agency is working to process outstanding agri-environment payments and agreements as soon as possible. We know how important these payments are to customers, which is why for Countryside Stewardship claimants, we will be making bridging payments worth 75% of their current claim value to farmers who have not received their advance payments in April.</p><p> </p><p>While our priority remains to deliver a negotiated deal, we fully recognise the concerns of the organics sector and are working hard to mitigate the impact of a no deal on organic operators.</p><p> </p><p>We have already confirmed that food and feed products that are certified as organic in the EU will be recognised after 29 March at the UKâs discretion. We are working to secure a reciprocal agreement so our operators can continue to export their organic produce to the EU.</p><p> </p><p>We currently have no plans to review rates of reward for organic farmers.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086592/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-18T13:10:19.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086592/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086592/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-03-11","Organic Farming","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans he has in place to (a) expedite agri-environment funding (i) applications and (ii) claims and (b) review rates of reward for the production of public goods to tackle the effect on the cash flow of organic farmers of leaving the EU without a deal.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","230680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086593","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-03-14","<p>No.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086593/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T14:21:19.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086593/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086593/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-03-11","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether UK military personnel on exchange programmes with the US Air Force are working in (a) in Yemen (b) in the skies above Yemen.","false","Biography information for Lloyd Russell-Moyle","Brighton, Kemptown","Lloyd Russell-Moyle","230883"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086594","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-03-14","<p>âI spoke to Sudanese Foreign Minister Dirdiri on 23 January and 13 March to express the strength of our ongoing concern at the use of violence, the decision to declare a state of emergency and to urge the government to respect the rights of the Sudanese people. In addition, I raised our concern regarding the response to protests in Sudan, including the use of lethal force, with the Sudanese Foreign Minister and emphasised the importance of respect for the rule of law and for human rights. Most recently the Sudanese ambassador was summoned to the Foreign Office on 7 March to register the depth of our ongoing concern at recent declarations which further erode human rights. We remain deeply concern at the human rights implication of the Government of Sudan's response to protests. We continue to monitor the situation and consider the best means to support human rights improvements in Sudan, including through official engagement, public messaging, and international fora.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086594/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T17:56:39.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086594/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086594/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-11","Sudan: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his Sudanese counterpart on human rights in that country, and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","230616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086595","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-03-14","<p>The RAF did not hold an aircraft on standby at RAF Northolt for the Prime Minister over the period in question.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086595/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T14:24:25.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086595/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086595/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-03-11","Prime Minister: Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the cost to the public purse was of providing a plane on standby at RAF Northolt for use by the Prime Minister from 8 to 11 March 2019 inclusive.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","230681"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086596","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-14","<p>The Department of Health and Social Care works extensively with the Department for International Trade to ensure that there is a clear cross-Government position on the protection of the National Health Service in future trade agreements. Additionally, the Parliamentary Under Secretary for Innovation (Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford) will be representing the Department of Health and Social Care in upcoming Cabinet-level discussions on future trade deals.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has repeatedly made its position on this clear - protecting public services, including the NHS, is of the utmost importance for the United Kingdom. The NHS is not, and never will be, for sale to the private sector, whether overseas or domestic. We will ensure that no trade agreements alter these fundamental facts.</p><p> </p><p>None of the trade agreements that we are party to as European Union members threaten or allow privatisation of public services, including the NHS. The Government will ensure that future trade deals include the necessary exclusions, exemptions, and reservations to ensure that decisions on how to run public services, including the NHS, will always remain the sole competence of UK governments, including the devolved administrations, and not our trade partners.</p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086596/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T10:48:12.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086596/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086596/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-11","NHS: Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent discussions he has held with the Secretary of State for International Trade on the potential role of the NHS in future trade deals after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","230617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086597","Department for Education","false","2019-03-19","<p>As at 31 January 2019, there were 200 commitments in England entered into the apprenticeship service, where the transfer of funds between apprenticeship service accounts has been approved (a commitment is where a potential apprentice, who is expected to go on to start an apprenticeship, has been recorded with the Apprenticeship Service). Of these transferred commitments as at 31 January 2019, there were 130 transferred commitments that had materialised into apprenticeship starts. More information is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/apprenticeship-and-levy-statistics-february-2019" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/apprenticeship-and-levy-statistics-february-2019</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Information on companies transferring apprenticeship levy funds in each region of England is not held centrally. Many levy-paying employers are headquartered in one region but operate across the country meaning that we cannot attribute levy-funds transferred in individual locations. Individual employers have control of the expenditure (and transfer) of apprenticeship levy funds based on their current and future skills needs.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086597/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-19T12:31:20.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086597/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086597/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-03-11","Apprentices: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate he has made of the number of companies who have transferred the apprenticeship levy in London.","false","Biography information for Bob Blackman","Harrow East","Bob Blackman","230796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086598","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-03-14","<p>We are aware of the ongoing demonstrations in Algeria and President Bouteflikaâs announcement that elections are to be postponed. We are following developments.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086598/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T15:57:54.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086598/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086598/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-11","Algeria: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment his Department has made of the level of political stability in Algeria; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","230618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086599","Treasury","false","2019-03-14","<p>Banks are under no obligation in law to inform customers of the reasons for an account closure.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, under s333A of the Proceeds of Crime Act 2002, it is a criminal offence for a person who has made a disclosure to the appropriate authorities under Part 7 (in relation to suspicions of money laundering) to inform the customer that they have done so, where that could prejudice an investigation. This applies to banks, where an account closure is the result of suspected criminal activity. Individual banks are responsible for compliance with this obligation<strong>. </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Salisbury","John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086599/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T12:49:28.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086599/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086599/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-03-11","Bank Services: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, on what statutory basis a bank is able to close an account without disclosure to the customer concerned.","false","Biography information for Laura Pidcock","North West Durham","Laura Pidcock","230884"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086600","Department for Education","false","2019-03-14","<p>No one should be held back from reaching their potential because of their gender or background. That is why my right hon. Friend, the Chancellor of the Exchequer announced in his Spring Statement on 13 March 2019 that the Department for Education will lead a scheme to provide free sanitary products in all secondary schools and colleges in England. The annual cost of this provision will depend on the specific nature of the delivery approach and we will refine costs as part of our policy development.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086600/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T17:18:10.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086600/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086600/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-03-11","Pupils: Sanitary Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent estimate his Department has made of the annual cost of providing free sanitary products to all girls in secondary schools in England.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","230619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086601","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-03-14","<p>It is vital that as housing supply increases, the quality of new build homes improves. We expect all housing developers to deliver good quality housing, to deliver it on time, and to treat house buyers fairly.</p><p>We know more needs to be done to strengthen consumer redress for purchasers of new build homes, we announced our intention for there to be a New Homes Ombudsman to protect the rights of homebuyers and hold developers to account.</p><p>When Parliamentary time allows, we intend to introduce legislation to require developers of new build homes to belong to a New Homes Ombudsman, which will be underpinned in statute.</p><p>We will consult on the detail of the proposed legislation to statutorily underpin a New Homes Ombudsman. This will include the approval mechanisms and standards that a New Homes Ombudsman must meet as well as whether a Code of Practice for developers should also be underpinned in legislation.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086601/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T14:06:32.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086601/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086601/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-03-11","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what recent assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the regulation of the new-build sector in relation to snagging issues.","false","Biography information for Laura Pidcock","North West Durham","Laura Pidcock","230885"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086602","Home Office","false","2019-03-19","<p>Endorsements for Start-up visas will be based on whether applicantsâ business ideas are innovative, viable and scalable. This assessment will be carried out by approved endorsing bodies, rather than by the Home Office.</p><p>Applicants will also need to prove their English language ability, have sufficient maintenance funds for themselves and any dependants and satisfy the standard checks which apply across the immigration system.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086602/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-19T14:51:10.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086602/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086602/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-11","Visas: New Businesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Written Statement of 7 March 2019 on Immigration Rules, HCWS1388, what criteria his Department plans to use to determine suitability for the category of start-up visa.","true","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","230620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086603","Home Office","false","2019-03-19","<p>Extensions and settlement in the Innovator category will be based on further assessment by an approved endorsing body</p><p>Endorsement for extension applications will assess whether applicants have made significant achievements against their business plans, and whether their businesses are trading. Applicants whose original business ideas do not succeed may re-apply, with a new business idea, for endorsement under the criteria for initial applications</p><p>Endorsements for settlement applications will be made against a range of criteria â covering investment, innovation, business growth and job creation â which applicants may choose from in order to qualify for settlement. Applicants may apply for accelerated settlement as soon as their businesses satisfy at least two of these criteria, providing they have spent at least three years in the category.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086603/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-19T14:54:54.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086603/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086603/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-11","Visas: New Businesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Written Statement of 7 March 2019 on Immigration Rules given by the Minister for Immigration on 7 March 2019, HCWS1388, what criteria his Department plans to use to determine the suitability for (a) an extension of an existing visa and (b) accelerated settlement.","true","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","230621"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086604","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-03-19","<p>We have provided training and advice to the Saudi Coalition, to support compliance with International Humanitarian Law (IHL). The British military has some of the highest standards in the world in how they conduct themselves in armed conflicts. We always seek to avoid civilian casualties and we are happy to share our hard-won experience with our partners. We regularly press, including at senior levels, the need for the Saudi-led Coalition to conduct thorough and conclusive investigations into reports of alleged violations of IHL.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086604/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-19T16:50:54.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086604/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086604/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-11","Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what financial and non-financial support the Government has provided to the Coalition Joint Impact Assessment Team in Yemen in (a) 2017, (b) 2018 and (c) 2019 to date.","true","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","230622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086605","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-03-19","<p>The Foreign Secretary raised the importance of humanitarian access with President Hadi during his meeting on 2 March. We channel UK funds through UN agencies and international Non-Governmental Organisations (NGOs) with a strong record of delivering and monitoring assistance. These organisations do everything they can under the most difficult circumstances to negotiate access, including in areas of active conflict, so that aid does get to those who need it most.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086605/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-19T16:54:06.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086605/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086605/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-11","Yemen: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assurances he received from the internationally recognised Government in Yemen that humanitarian aid is able to reach Yemeni citizens during his visit to Yemen on 3 March 2019.","true","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","230623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086606","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-03-14","<p>We have made no assessment of the number of UK citizens in refugee camps in Iraq, Jordan, Lebanon, Syria and Turkey.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086606/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T16:54:48.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086606/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086606/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-11","Middle East: Migrant Camps","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent estimate his Department has made of the number of UK citizens living in refugee camps in (a) Iraq, (b) Jordan, (c) Lebanon, (d) Syria and (e) Turkey.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","230624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086607","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-03-19","<p>While visiting the port of Aden, the Foreign Secretary met aid workers, including representatives of the Aden Office of the UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA) to discuss the humanitarian response to the Yemeni conflict. We continue to support and seek further information where appropriate from Non-Governmental Organisations (NGOs) and civil-society organisations.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086607/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-19T17:02:47.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086607/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086607/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-11","Yemen: Third Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what meetings he held with civil-society organisations during his visit to Yemen on 3 March 2019.","true","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","230625"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086608","Department for International Development","false","2019-03-18","<p>The International Organisation for Migration (IOM) estimates that 73,190 Yemenis returned to Yemen from Saudi Arabia in 2018.</p><p> </p><p>Data was not collected by IOM in 2017 and they are yet to release data for 2019.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086608/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-18T17:32:24.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086608/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086608/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-03-11","Yemen: Migration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what estimate her Department has made of the number of Yemenis who have migrated from Saudi Arabia to Yemen in (a) 2017, (b) 2018 and (c) 2019 to date.","true","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","230626"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086609","Department for International Trade","false","2019-03-14","<p>I refer the Honourable Friend for Leicester East to the answer I gave to the Member for Midlothian on 26 February 2019, UIN 224362.</p>","Meon Valley","George Hollingbery","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086609/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T16:37:39.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086609/answer","Biography information for Sir George Hollingbery","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086609/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-03-11","Trade Agreements: Public Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, if he will ensure that (a) the NHS and (b) other public services are excluded from future trade deals.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","230627"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086610","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-14","<p>Respiratory disease is a clinical priority within the recently published NHS Long Term Plan. The Plan has the overarching objective of improving outcomes for people with respiratory disease, including asthma.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England supports the national asthma audit programme that provides data on a range of indicators to show improvements and opportunities for further improvements in asthma outcomes.</p><p> </p><p>The recently published general practitioner (GP) contract has made improvements to the Quality and Outcomes framework through the introduction of quality improvement modules. This replaces the current system of exception reporting with a personalised care adjustment approach, which will better reflect individual clinical situations and patientsâ wishes. NHS England and GPC England have agreed to an ongoing programme of indicator review in key priority areas, including asthma in 2019/20. Through the GP contract and Primary Care Networks, clinical pharmacists will take responsibility for the care management of patients with chronic diseases and undertake clinical medication reviews to proactively manage people with complex polypharmacy, and those with multiple long term conditions, in particular people with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease and asthma.</p><p> </p><p>National programmes such NHS RightCare are using leading edge medical evidence and practical support to help local health economies to make best use of their resources and using tested evidence based processes to make sustainable improvements to patient care. As part of this programme, a RightCare asthma pathway will be published in the spring which will outline the optimal pathway for patients, including the need for follow-up appointments following emergency care.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086610/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T17:01:30.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086610/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086610/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-11","Asthma","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to the finding in Asthma UK's report, The Reality of Asthma Care in the UK -  Annual Asthma Survey 2018 that two-thirds of patients do not receive a follow-up appointment with their GP after receiving emergency care, if he will take steps tackle the reasons for that finding.","false","Biography information for Paul Farrelly","Newcastle-under-Lyme","Paul Farrelly","230635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086611","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-03-14","<p>Local authorities are responsible for funding the maintenance of their district heating systems and for all maintenance of their housing stock mostly using the rental income and service charges they receive which since 2012 under Self-Financing they have been able to retain in full.</p><p>In England, the Regulator of Social Housing requires registered providers to maintain their homes to the Decent Homes Standard, which says homes must have efficient heating. Homes are also required to be free of serious hazards, such as excess cold, identified using the Housing Health and Safety Rating System (HHSRS).</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086611/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T14:25:57.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086611/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086611/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-03-11","District Heating","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what funding the Government can provide to local councils to replace unreliable and ageing district heating systems.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","230797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086612","Department for Transport","false","2019-03-18","<p>Highways England published comprehensive evaluation reports for the first three years of operation of the M25 junctions 5-7 and 23-27 all lane running schemes on 16 July 2018. These included information on non-compliance and on a programme of work designed to improve Red X compliance.</p><p>The evidence indicates an overall improvement in the Red-X compliance rate on both schemes between the three-year and one-year reports. The majority of drivers obey Red-X signals. Highways England continue to work closely with the Police to issue warning letters to drivers who fail to comply with a Red-X signal, as well as running a range of driver information campaigns.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086612/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-18T13:24:01.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086612/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086612/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-03-11","Road Traffic Offences: Motorways","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of trends in the level of red-X non-compliance on smart motorways for each of the last two years for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","Hemel Hempstead","Sir Mike Penning","230682"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086613","Department for Transport","false","2019-03-13","<p>The Department does not collect data on whether people killed or seriously injured were alongside or in the presence of a stationary vehicle using a warning beacon emitting a flashing light and for what purpose.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086613/answer",,,,,"230684 ; 230685","2019-03-13T15:08:44.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086613/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086613/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-03-11","Roads: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many people were killed or seriously injured on the roadside when they were in the presence of a stationary vehicle using a warning beacon emitting a flashing red light in each of the last three years for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","Hemel Hempstead","Sir Mike Penning","230683"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086614","Department for Transport","false","2019-03-13","<p>The Department does not collect data on whether people killed or seriously injured were alongside or in the presence of a stationary vehicle using a warning beacon emitting a flashing light and for what purpose.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086614/answer",,,,,"230683 ; 230685","2019-03-13T15:08:44.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086614/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086614/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-03-11","Roads: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many people were killed or seriously injured on the roadside when they were in the presence of a stationary vehicle using a warning beacon emitting flashing an amber light in each of the last 10 years for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","Hemel Hempstead","Sir Mike Penning","230684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086615","Department for Transport","false","2019-03-13","<p>The Department does not collect data on whether people killed or seriously injured were alongside or in the presence of a stationary vehicle using a warning beacon emitting a flashing light and for what purpose.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086615/answer",,,,,"230683 ; 230684","2019-03-13T15:08:45.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086615/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086615/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-03-11","Roads: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many people were killed or seriously injured working alongside a stationary vehicle using a flashing amber warning beacon permitted for the purpose of (a) collecting refuse, (b) road clearance, (c) inspecting, cleansing, maintaining, adjusting, renewing or installing any apparatus which is in, on, under or over a road, (d) testing, maintaining, improving, cleansing or watering roads and (e) surveying in each of the last 10 years for which data is available; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","Hemel Hempstead","Sir Mike Penning","230685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086616","Department for Transport","false","2019-03-18","<p>The original safety assessment of All Lane Running (ALR) included the safety of a vehicle stopping in a running lane during peak and off-peak periods. It also identified a range of measures, such as the provision of traffic management technology and emergency areas, designed to ensure that overall ALR safety levels would be at least as safe as those of a traditional motorway with a hard shoulder.</p><p>The smart motorway schemes between junctions 5-7 and 23-27 of the M25 were the first to be designed to the ALR standard, and were completed in 2014. The performance of both schemes was monitored, and reports were published after one, two and three years of operation, which included an assessment of safety and performance data.</p><p>M25 three-year evaluation reports:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/m25-junction-5-to-7-third-year-evaluation-report" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/m25-junction-5-to-7-third-year-evaluation-report</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/m25-junction-23-to-27-third-year-evaluation-report" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/m25-junction-23-to-27-third-year-evaluation-report</a></p><p>The reviews show that the All Lane Running sections are performing in line with expectations, successfully increasing capacity and improving journeys for motorists. These reviews also found that the M25 schemes delivered a 27% safety improvement overall.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086616/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-18T15:48:53.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086616/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086616/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-03-11","Motorways","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make a comparative risk assessment of the safety of a vehicle stopping in a running lane during off peak times on (a) an all lane running motorway and (b) a traditional motorway with a hard shoulder.","false","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","Hemel Hempstead","Sir Mike Penning","230686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086617","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-03-15","<p>Up until September 2018, 132,429 households received ECO measures within the West Midlands. This equates to 117 households per 1,000 households receiving ECO measures compared to 72 households per 1,000 households for Great Britain. These published statistics can be found here (Table 4.4): <a href="https://emea01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.gov.uk%2Fgovernment%2Fstatistics%2Fhousehold-energy-efficiency-statistics-headline-release-february-2019&amp;data=02%7C01%7CSaira.Ali%40beis.gov.uk%7Ce8ea64ee7a734544308408d6a6e4a7f8%7Ccbac700502c143ebb497e6492d1b2dd8%7C0%7C0%7C636879898327441811&amp;sdata=ep%2B1OGeVetv5lhJGxqvBz3CDgTX1dpHJoMKPQ7UDBGU%3D&amp;reserved=0" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/household-energy-efficiency-statistics-headline-release-february-2019</a></p><p> </p><p>BEIS does not hold information on the amount of Energy Company Obligation (ECO) funding that is allocated to individual areas. Neither does BEIS project where spending will occur in the future.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086617/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-15T12:01:13.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086617/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086617/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-03-11","Energy Companies Obligation: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, with reference to the Government's Clean Growth Strategy, what estimate he has made of the amount and proportion of the Â£3.6 billion Energy Company Obligation that will be allocated to the West Midlands metro area; over what time period that allocation will be spent; and what estimate he has made of the number of homes that will benefit from that allocation.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","230636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086618","Department for Transport","false","2019-03-14","<p>At the end of September 2018, there were 1,210,559 vehicles registered to a private keeper at an address in the West Midlands Metropolitan County, of which 2,903 were battery electric vehicles, 885 were plug-in hybrid electric vehicles, 9,959 were hybrid electric vehicles, and 121 were range-extended electric vehicles.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086618/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T10:25:59.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086618/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086618/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-03-11","Motor Vehicles: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many privately owned vehicles are registered in the West Midlands metro area; and how many of those vehicles are electric vehicles.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","230637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086619","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-03-19","<p>In 2016 we announced an improved offer making available Â£4.5m to 2020 to Local Authorities wishing to install recharging infrastructure in residential areas for drivers of electric cars that lack offstreet parking through our On-street Residential Chargepoint Scheme. 28 Local Authorities have applied to the scheme to date including Coventry City Council who have been awarded Â£300,000 to install 90 chargepoints. Additionally, as part of OLEVâs Â£20m Taxi Infrastructure Competition, Coventry, Wolverhampton and Birmingham were between them awarded over Â£4.5m in 2017 to help deliver charging infrastructure dedicated to ultra-low emission taxis. The Midlands was one of the eight âPlugged-in Placesâ projects and received over Â£2.5m from the Office for Low Emission Vehicles. Between December 2010 and 2013, the project helped develop a regional network of more than 850 electric vehicle Charging Points across both the East and West Midlands. The total funding amount awarded across the East and West Midlands for these schemes is Â£7.3 million.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086619/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-19T16:42:29.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086619/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086619/answer","Watford","Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086619/answer/previousversion/107889","Biography information for Richard Harrington","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-03-11","Charging Points: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what funding has been allocated to the West Midlands Combined Authority for the expansion of electric vehicle charging infrastructure; and over what time period that funding has been allocated.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","230638"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086620","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-03-20","<p>BEIS holds data for electricity generation from renewable sources at a local authority level. We do not hold data for renewable heat production or liquid biofuel production at this level of regional disaggregation. The latest available figures are for 2017, these are published here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/regional-renewable-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/regional-renewable-statistics</a>.</p><p> </p><p>271 GWh of electricity was generated from renewable sources in the West Midlands metropolitan area in 2017. This accounted for 0.3 per cent of the UK total. This is calculated as an aggregate of the generation within the following local authority areas: Birmingham, Coventry, Dudley, Sandwell, Solihull, Walsall and Wolverhampton.</p><p> </p><p>2078 GWh of electricity was generated in the West Midlands region from renewable sources in 2017. This accounted for 2.1 per cent of the UK total.</p><p> </p><p>Data for 2018 will be published in September 2019.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086620/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-20T11:26:25.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086620/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086620/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-03-11","Renewable Energy: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what proportion of the UKâs renewable energy supply in the last 12 months was generated from the West Midlands metro area.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","230639"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086621","Department for International Trade","false","2019-03-14","<p>I refer the Honourable Friend for Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath to the answer I gave to the Member for Midlothian on 26 February 2019, UIN 224362.</p>","Meon Valley","George Hollingbery","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086621/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T16:43:10.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086621/answer","Biography information for Sir George Hollingbery","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086621/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-03-11","Trade Agreements: Public Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps he is taking to help ensure that the NHS and other public services will not be included in future trade agreements for services after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Lesley Laird","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Lesley Laird","230886"
