"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086639","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-03-19","<p>Sentencing is a matter for our independent courts, who take into account all circumstances of the case, including any aggravating and mitigating factors. We are clear that sentencing must match the severity of a crime.</p><p> </p><p>However, sentences should also rehabilitate. There is persuasive evidence showing community sentences, in certain circumstances, are more effective than short custodial sentences in reducing reoffending. The MoJ study âThe impact of short custodial sentences, community orders and suspended sentence orders on re-offendingâ published in 2015 found that over a 1-year follow up period, a higher proportion of people re-offended having been sentenced to custody of under 12 months without supervision on release than other similar people given community orders.</p><p> </p><p>Unless we tackle the underlying causes of offending, we cannot protect the public from being victims of crime. Effective community orders can address offendersâ behaviour, answer their mental health and alcohol or drug misuse needs, and provide reparation for the benefit of the wider community.</p><p> </p><p>Data on the highest number of previous offences committed by an offender who received their first immediate custodial sentence can be viewed in the table. This information is broken down by males and females, and covers the period year ending September 2014 â year ending September 2018.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086639/answer","PQ 230697 Response Table.xlsx","PQ 230697 Response Table.xlsx","Table for PQ 230697","Table for PQ 230697",,"2019-03-19T17:29:29.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086639/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086639/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-03-11","Prison Sentences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the highest number of total previous offences a (a) male and (b) female offender committed before being given an immediate custodial sentence in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","230697"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086640","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-03-19","<p>Sentencing is a matter for our independent courts, who take into account all circumstances of the case, including any aggravating and mitigating factors. We are clear that sentencing must match the severity of a crime.</p><p> </p><p>However, sentences should also rehabilitate. There is persuasive evidence showing community sentences, in certain circumstances, are more effective than short custodial sentences in reducing reoffending. The MoJ study âThe impact of short custodial sentences, community orders and suspended sentence orders on re-offendingâ published in 2015 found that over a 1-year follow up period, a higher proportion of people re-offended having been sentenced to custody of under 12 months without supervision on release than other similar people given community orders.</p><p> </p><p>Unless we tackle the underlying causes of offending, we cannot protect the public from being victims of crime. Effective community orders can address offendersâ behaviour, answer their mental health and alcohol or drug misuse needs, and provide reparation for the benefit of the wider community.</p><p> </p><p>Data on the highest number of previous cautions and convictions for a selected offence type for a person who received their first immediate custodial sentence for the selected offence type, covering the period year ending September 2016 â year ending September 2018, can be viewed in the table.</p><p> </p><p>The data provided in the accompanying response table is sourced from MoJ's extract of the Police National Computer. As benefit fraud offences are not prosecuted by the police, we are unable to answer PQ230707.</p><p> </p><p>Caution should be exercised in drawing general conclusions from this data. By definition these are the very extremes of the system â the individuals with the very most convictions. Most significantly the 2015 study suggests that giving a short custodial sentence to a prolific offender is more, not less, likely to result in them committing another offence after custody, compared to giving them a community sentence.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086640/answer","230698 - 230707; 231412 - 231416 Response Table.xlsx","230698 - 230707; 231412 - 231416 Response Table.xlsx","230698 - 230707; 231412 - 231416 Response Table","230698 - 230707; 231412 - 231416 Response Table","230699 ; 230700 ; 230701 ; 230702 ; 230703 ; 230704 ; 230705 ; 230706 ; 230707 ; 231412 ; 231413 ; 231414 ; 231415 ; 231416","2019-03-19T17:54:29.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086640/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086640/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-03-11","Knives: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the highest number of total previous offences for possession of a blade or point a person committed before being given an immediate custodial sentence for that offence in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","230698"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086641","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-03-14","<p>Local authorities are responsible for allocating public funding to youth services in their area in line with local need. We believe they are best placed to know what is required in their communities.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has made over Â£200bn available to local authorities to spend on local services over this Spending Review.</p>","Eastleigh","Mims Davies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086641/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T14:08:05.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086641/answer","Biography information for Mims Davies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086641/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-03-11","Youth Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment his Department has made of the total reduction in central Government funding for youth services provided by local authorities in England since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","230801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086642","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-03-19","<p>Sentencing is a matter for our independent courts, who take into account all circumstances of the case, including any aggravating and mitigating factors. We are clear that sentencing must match the severity of a crime.</p><p> </p><p>However, sentences should also rehabilitate. There is persuasive evidence showing community sentences, in certain circumstances, are more effective than short custodial sentences in reducing reoffending. The MoJ study âThe impact of short custodial sentences, community orders and suspended sentence orders on re-offendingâ published in 2015 found that over a 1-year follow up period, a higher proportion of people re-offended having been sentenced to custody of under 12 months without supervision on release than other similar people given community orders.</p><p> </p><p>Unless we tackle the underlying causes of offending, we cannot protect the public from being victims of crime. Effective community orders can address offendersâ behaviour, answer their mental health and alcohol or drug misuse needs, and provide reparation for the benefit of the wider community.</p><p> </p><p>Data on the highest number of previous cautions and convictions for a selected offence type for a person who received their first immediate custodial sentence for the selected offence type, covering the period year ending September 2016 â year ending September 2018, can be viewed in the table.</p><p> </p><p>The data provided in the accompanying response table is sourced from MoJ's extract of the Police National Computer. As benefit fraud offences are not prosecuted by the police, we are unable to answer PQ230707.</p><p> </p><p>Caution should be exercised in drawing general conclusions from this data. By definition these are the very extremes of the system â the individuals with the very most convictions. Most significantly the 2015 study suggests that giving a short custodial sentence to a prolific offender is more, not less, likely to result in them committing another offence after custody, compared to giving them a community sentence.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086642/answer","230698 - 230707; 231412 - 231416 Response Table.xlsx","230698 - 230707; 231412 - 231416 Response Table.xlsx","230698 - 230707; 231412 - 231416 Response Table","230698 - 230707; 231412 - 231416 Response Table","230698 ; 230700 ; 230701 ; 230702 ; 230703 ; 230704 ; 230705 ; 230706 ; 230707 ; 231412 ; 231413 ; 231414 ; 231415 ; 231416","2019-03-19T17:54:29.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086642/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086642/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-03-11","Offensive Weapons: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the highest number of previous offences for possession of an offensive weapon was that a person committed before being given an immediate custodial sentence for that offence in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","230699"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086643","Department for Education","false","2019-03-14","<p>The Department does not hold data on the number of children daily reading unaided in England. The Department does, however, hold figures on pupilsâ performance in reading assessments. This is an indicator of pupilsâ ability to read unaided. A new, more rigorous national curriculum has been taught in primary schools since September 2014 and new tests and assessments based on this curriculum were first taken by pupils in summer 2016. Since 2016, the proportion of pupils reaching the expected standard in the reading test at the end of key stage 2 has risen from 66% to 75% in 2018.</p><p> </p><p>Regarding pupils in the earlier stages of reading, in 2018 there were 163,000 more 6 year olds in England on track to become fluent readers compared to in 2012. This represented 82% of pupils meeting the expected standard in the year 1 phonics screening check, compared to just 58% when the check was introduced in 2012. Regarding pupils who met the expected standard in phonics in year 1 in 2013, 88% went on to meet the expected standard in the key stage 2 reading test in 2018.</p><p> </p><p>England achieved its highest ever score in reading in 2016, moving from joint 10th place to joint 8th place in the most recent Progress in International Reading Literacy Study rankings. This follows a greater focus on reading in the primary curriculum and a particular focus on phonics.</p><p> </p><p>A national network of 32 primary schools across England has been appointed to become English Hubs, backed by Â£26.3 million funding. In addition to improving the teaching of phonics and early language development, these schools will champion reading for pleasure in the schools that they support.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086643/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T16:49:56.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086643/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086643/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-03-11","Literacy: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent assessment his Department has made of trends in the number of children daily reading unaided in England.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","230802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086644","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-03-19","<p>Sentencing is a matter for our independent courts, who take into account all circumstances of the case, including any aggravating and mitigating factors. We are clear that sentencing must match the severity of a crime.</p><p> </p><p>However, sentences should also rehabilitate. There is persuasive evidence showing community sentences, in certain circumstances, are more effective than short custodial sentences in reducing reoffending. The MoJ study âThe impact of short custodial sentences, community orders and suspended sentence orders on re-offendingâ published in 2015 found that over a 1-year follow up period, a higher proportion of people re-offended having been sentenced to custody of under 12 months without supervision on release than other similar people given community orders.</p><p> </p><p>Unless we tackle the underlying causes of offending, we cannot protect the public from being victims of crime. Effective community orders can address offendersâ behaviour, answer their mental health and alcohol or drug misuse needs, and provide reparation for the benefit of the wider community.</p><p> </p><p>Data on the highest number of previous cautions and convictions for a selected offence type for a person who received their first immediate custodial sentence for the selected offence type, covering the period year ending September 2016 â year ending September 2018, can be viewed in the table.</p><p> </p><p>The data provided in the accompanying response table is sourced from MoJ's extract of the Police National Computer. As benefit fraud offences are not prosecuted by the police, we are unable to answer PQ230707.</p><p> </p><p>Caution should be exercised in drawing general conclusions from this data. By definition these are the very extremes of the system â the individuals with the very most convictions. Most significantly the 2015 study suggests that giving a short custodial sentence to a prolific offender is more, not less, likely to result in them committing another offence after custody, compared to giving them a community sentence.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086644/answer","230698 - 230707; 231412 - 231416 Response Table.xlsx","230698 - 230707; 231412 - 231416 Response Table.xlsx","230698 - 230707; 231412 - 231416 Response Table","230698 - 230707; 231412 - 231416 Response Table","230698 ; 230699 ; 230701 ; 230702 ; 230703 ; 230704 ; 230705 ; 230706 ; 230707 ; 231412 ; 231413 ; 231414 ; 231415 ; 231416","2019-03-19T17:54:29.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086644/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086644/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-03-11","Crimes of Violence: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the highest number of previous offences for assault was that a person committed before being given an immediate custodial sentence for that offence in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","230700"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086645","Department for Education","false","2019-03-14","<p>The information requested, regarding statistics showing excluded pupils who did not return to full-time education, is not held centrally. Local authorities are responsible for arranging suitable full-time education for permanently excluded pupils, which must begin no later than the sixth day of the exclusion.</p><p> </p><p>Statistics on exclusions in academic year 2017/18 are not yet available. Exclusion statistics covering 2016/17 are available in the National Statistics release 'Permanent and fixed-period exclusions in England 2016 to 2017'.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/permanent-and-fixed-period-exclusions-in-england-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/permanent-and-fixed-period-exclusions-in-england-2016-to-2017</a>.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086645/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T17:27:15.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086645/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086645/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-03-11","Pupil Exclusions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps his Department has taken to estimate the number of children in England who were permanently excluded from a school and did not return to full time education in in the academic year 2017-2018.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","230803"
