"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086757","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-03-18","<p>My rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State, rather than The Planning Inspectorate, is the decision-maker for applications for consent for nationally significant infrastructure projects under the Planning Act 2008.</p><p>On 30 July 2018, he directed that the AQUIND interconnector should be treated as a nationally significant infrastructure project.</p><p>The processes for assessing such projects under the Planning Act are designed to allow the full participation of both local communities and relevant local authorities.</p><p>Local authorities have a very important role in the process. They are encouraged to discuss and work through the issues raised by proposals with prospective applicants well before the application is submitted, and to engage with applicants in the preparation of statements of common ground.</p><p>Local authorities will also be asked to consider the prospective applicantâs proposals for consultation with the local community and then comment upon the quality of that consultation.</p><p>During the examination of the application, there will be further opportunities for local authorities, local people and any other parties with an interest in the project to make representations.</p><p>Relevant local authorities will also be invited to submit a local impact report giving details of the likely impact of the proposed development on the authorityâs area.</p><p>In coming to a decision, the Secretary of State must have regard to any local impact reports that are submitted.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086757/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-18T15:11:51.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086757/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086757/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-03-11","Electricity Interconnectors: Planning Permission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the effect of the decision-making authority of Planning Inspectorate for the development of the AQUIND interconnector on the effectiveness of local democracy.","false","Biography information for Stephen Morgan","Portsmouth South","Stephen Morgan","230919"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086758","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-03-18","<p>The reasons why my rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State issued a direction under S35 of the Planning Act 2008 in respect of the AQUIND interconnector are set out in the notice of that direction dated 30 July 2018 which is published on The Planning Inspectorateâs website - <a href="https://infrastructure.planninginspectorate.gov.uk/wp-content/ipc/uploads/projects/EN020022/EN020022-000013-Section%2035%20Direction%20notice%20AQUIND%20Interconnector_30July2018.pdf" target="_blank">https://infrastructure.planninginspectorate.gov.uk/wp-content/ipc/uploads/projects/EN020022/EN020022-000013-Section%2035%20Direction%20notice%20AQUIND%20Interconnector_30July2018.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State would be the decision-maker on any application for consent for the AQUIND interconnector made in accordance with that direction, following the examination of the application by The Planning Inspectorate.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086758/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-18T15:11:58.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086758/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086758/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-03-11","Electricity Interconnectors: Planning Permission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the evidential basis was for the decision to provide the Planning Inspectorate with decision-making powers for the development of the AQUIND interconnector.","false","Biography information for Stephen Morgan","Portsmouth South","Stephen Morgan","230920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086759","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-03-20","<p>No application for consent for an interconnector has been submitted under the Planning Act 2008 regime.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086759/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-20T11:26:46.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086759/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086759/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-03-11","Electricity Interconnectors: Planning Permission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether an interconnector development has taken place as a result of a decision by the Planning Inspectorate; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Morgan","Portsmouth South","Stephen Morgan","230921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086760","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-03-15","<p>The Government recognises the critical role that post offices play in communities and for small businesses across the UK. This is why the Government committed to safeguard the post office network and protect existing rural services. The overall number of post offices across the UK remains at its most stable in decades with over 11,500 branches thanks to significant Government investment of over Â£2 billion since 2010.</p><p> </p><p>While the Government sets the strategic direction for the Post Office, it allows the company the commercial freedom to deliver this strategy as an independent business. Matters relating to postmasters, network transformation and the operation of post offices by retailers are operational matters for the Post Office. I have therefore asked Post Office Limited to write to the hon Member on these matters. A copy of her reply will be placed in the Libraries of the House.</p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086760/answer",,,,,"230832 ; 230835 ; 230836","2019-03-15T12:01:55.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086760/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086760/answer","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086760/answer/previousversion/107881","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-03-11","Post Offices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many temporary sub-postmasters are currently operating branches in (a) Scotland, (b) Wales, (c) Northern Ireland, and (d) each region of England.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","230837"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086761","Department for Education","false","2019-03-19","<p>The Government is committed to supporting the education of all children and young people with special educational needs or a disability, including those with a hearing impairment.</p><p> </p><p>Schools may choose to offer British Sign Language (BSL) in their individual school curriculum or include it as part of their extra-curricular activities programme. There are existing accredited BSL qualifications at Levels 1,2,3,4 and 6, for which schools may enter pupils at any point in their school careers.</p><p> </p><p>The Department and Ofqual (the independent qualifications regulator) have received a proposal for a BSL GCSE from the exam board Signature. All GCSEs need to meet certain subject content and assessment requirements to ensure that they are of the standard expected of GCSEs. The Department is now developing draft BSL GCSE subject content, which will be considered against the subject content criteria requirements that apply to all GCSEs. If these expectations are met and a BSL GCSE is ready to be introduced, the Department will then consider whether to make an exception to our general rule that there should be no new GCSEs in this Parliament.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086761/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-19T14:38:26.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086761/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086761/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-03-11","Sign Language: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps he is taking to allow students to study British Sign Language at school.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","230726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086762","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-19","<p>The Government is committed to making the United Kingdom home of genomic healthcare. The National Genomic Healthcare Strategy, which we plan to launch in autumn 2019, will set out how the genomics community can work together to make the UK the global leader. We will be leading a national conversation to develop the strategy, which will include comprehensive engagement with a wide range of stakeholders.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086762/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-19T14:12:37.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086762/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086762/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-11","Genetics: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, when the National Genomic Strategy will be launched; and what opportunities there will be for stakeholder involvement in that strategy's development.","false","Biography information for Chris Green","Bolton West","Chris Green","230838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086763","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-19","<p>Our bold aspiration is to sequence five million genomes in the United Kingdom over the next five years. Through UK Biobank and NHS England, we already have commitments to sequence at least one million whole genomes. We will set develop our plans for the remaining four million as part of the National Genomic Healthcare Strategy, announced on 27 February 2019. We anticipate working with partners in the devolved administrations, research institutions, charities and industry to realise this ambition.</p><p> </p><p>The whole genome sequencing of the UK Biobank participants will reflect the diverse volunteer population. The whole genome sequencing through the NHS Genomic Medicine Service will be done for those eligible under the National Genomic Test Directory in order to provide consistent and equitable access to genomic medicine and sequencing. We will fully consider diversity issues as part of the delivery of the wider five million ambition.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086763/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-19T14:11:43.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086763/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086763/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-11","Genetics: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how his goal to sequence five million genomes will be realised; and what steps his Department will take to ensure that participants reflect the demographic make-up of the population.","false","Biography information for Chris Green","Bolton West","Chris Green","230839"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086764","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-03-22","<p>The Government is currently considering the format of the statutory review of the Pubs Code and the Pubs Code Adjudicator and will ensure all those with an interest have an opportunity to contribute to the review.</p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086764/answer",,,,,"230841","2019-03-22T11:45:38.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086764/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086764/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-03-11","Public Houses: Codes of Practice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will take steps to ensure that the upcoming Pubs Code review includes a full public consultation.","false","Biography information for Chris Green","Bolton West","Chris Green","230840"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086765","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-03-22","<p>The Government is currently considering the format of the statutory review of the Pubs Code and the Pubs Code Adjudicator and will ensure all those with an interest have an opportunity to contribute to the review.</p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086765/answer",,,,,"230840","2019-03-22T11:45:38.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086765/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086765/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-03-11","Public Houses: Codes of Practice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether consumers will have the opportunity to share their views as part of the review into the Pubs Code.","false","Biography information for Chris Green","Bolton West","Chris Green","230841"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086766","Wales Office","false","2019-03-14","<p>The Office of the Secretary of State for Wales supports the aims of Earth Hour and will be fully participating on 30 March. The Office will be turning off any non-essential electric lights at our London and Cardiff offices from 20:30 to 21:30 on that day.</p><p> </p>","Selby and Ainsty","Nigel Adams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086766/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T11:31:51.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086766/answer","Biography information for Nigel Adams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086766/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2019-03-11","Wales Office: Earth Hour","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what plans his Department has for participation in Earth Hour on 30 March 2019.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","230656"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086767","Wales Office","false","2019-03-14","<p>I have regular discussions with the Minister for the Cabinet Office and the Minister for the Constitution on a range of issues, including electoral matters. The Governmentâs major reforms to the electoral registration system, including the introduction of Individual Electoral Registration have resulted in record levels of electors registering to vote in Wales and participating in our democracy.</p><p> </p><p>The Government set out its priorities for democratic engagement for 2019 and beyond in its report <em>Democratic Engagement: Respecting, Protecting and Promoting Our Democracy</em>, published in January. The report highlights the Government's commitment to ensuring everyone can make their voice heard free from abuse, making voting easier and more accessible for vulnerable and under-registered groups, and introducing measures to protect electorsâ votes.</p><p> </p><p>The Wales Act 2017 devolved powers over National Assembly elections and local government elections in Wales. Officials from the UK Government and the Welsh Government are discussing areas for greater collaboration such as canvass reform and voter registration.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086767/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T17:29:37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086767/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086767/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2019-03-11","Electoral Register: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what recent discussions he has had with the Minister for the Cabinet Office on increasing electoral registration and voter turnout in Wales.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","230657"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086768","Wales Office","false","2019-03-14","<p>The Office of the Secretary of State for Wales has to date spent Â£17,400 on external consultants in the current financial year. The Office spent nothing on external consultants in the previous three financial years.</p>","Selby and Ainsty","Nigel Adams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086768/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T11:33:44.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086768/answer","Biography information for Nigel Adams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086768/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2019-03-11","Wales Office: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how much his Department has spent on external consultants in each of the last four years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","230658"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086769","Wales Office","false","2019-03-14","<p>All statistical datasets collected or collated by the Office of the Secretary of State for Wales are published except datasets that include personal data.</p>","Selby and Ainsty","Nigel Adams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086769/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T11:32:50.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086769/answer","Biography information for Nigel Adams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086769/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2019-03-11","Wales Office: Statistics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what proportion of statistical datasets collected or collated by his Department are made publicly available.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","230659"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086770","Department for Transport","false","2019-03-19","<p>According to the Rail Delivery Group, there were 10,400 vehicles in passenger use in 1996/97 compared to 14,025 as at March 2018, an increase of over 3,500 vehicles.</p><p> </p><p>This additional fleet capacity is helping to lengthen trains and contribute towards the thousands of extra rail services each week. In addition, the rail industry reports a major increase in the efficient utilisation of the rolling stock fleet since 1995, in particular through much improved use of spare capacity at off-peak times. Further,, changes to trains types and their internal layouts has led to the average capacity of trains increasing substantially. For example through the replacement of slam-door carriages, introduction of trains with metro-style interiors and changes to seating configurations.</p><p> </p><p>Various infrastructure enhancements have also been made across the country, with around Â£15billion being spent in CP5 between 2014 and 2019 on rail infrastructure upgrades. This includes various capacity enhancement projects such as additional platforms, for example at Liverpool Lime Street and Manchester airport stations; platform lengthening, for example at London Waterloo and some other stations across the South East; and rail line capacity upgrades, such as four-tracking between Huyton and Roby on the Liverpool to Manchester route, track and signalling improvements on the Calder Valley route between Manchester and Bradford via Halifax, re-signalling between Plymouth and Penzance, and four-tracking on the Filton Bank in Bristol.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086770/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-19T17:08:46.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086770/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086770/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-03-11","Railways: Passengers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 7 March 2019 to Question 226656 on Railways: Passengers, what corresponding increases in capacity in the form of (a) new rolling stock and (b) infrastructure enhancements have been provided by the rail industry in each of the last 30 years.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","230842"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086771","Department for Transport","false","2019-03-18","<p>Carbon budgets are not set by individual departments.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086771/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-18T12:24:13.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086771/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086771/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-03-11","Department for Transport: Carbon Budgets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what carbon budget his Department has set for this year and each of the next (a) five, (b) 10 and (c) 15 years.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","230843"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086772","Department for Transport","false","2019-03-19","<p>During the development of the scheme HS2 Ltd has sought to assess the capacity of the rail freight industry to support its plans to transfer excavated and construction materials by rail. HS2 Ltdâs understanding of the volume of material that will need to be transported by rail continue to be refined. HS2 Ltd and its supply chain continue to engage with the rail industry to move these plans forward. As plans become more certain, HS2 Ltd and its supply chain are seeking to secure rail freight support, including making applications to Network Rail for timetable capacity allocation through the standard industry process. The first of these requests has been submitted, in time for the December 2019 timetable change.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086772/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-19T15:18:58.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086772/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086772/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-03-11","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the capacity of the rail freight industry to support the construction of High Speed Two.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","230844"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086773","Department for International Trade","false","2019-03-14","<p>The Exporting is GREAT campaign works closely with hundreds of UK companies and scores of partners to encourage more companies to start exporting or to export more.</p><p> </p><p>These partners include professional services firms, banks, major online businesses, business representative organisations and trade / professional bodies.</p><p> </p><p>These companies give their time freely, at no cost to the public purse beyond the resource cost required to manage and support their involvement. It is not possible to separate these specific costs from the overall Exporting is GREAT campaign costs</p>","Beverley and Holderness","Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086773/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T16:34:40.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086773/answer","Biography information for Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086773/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-03-11","Exports: Advertising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, pursuant to the Answer of 11 March 2019 to Question 229270 on Exports: Advertising, what estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of the Exporting is Great campaign working with (a) private sector partners, and (b) a network of exporters to promote exporting.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","230922"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086774","Department for Education","false","2019-03-15","<p>On Secondary National Offer Day on 1 March, the vast majority of parents will have been offered a place at one of their preferred schools. The 2018 data showed that last year more than nine in ten pupils got a place at one of their top three choices setting them on the path for a successful future. Standards have also risen since 2010 with 86% of schools now judged as good or outstanding, compared to 68% in 2010, meaning there are more good schools for parents to send their children to.</p><p>The Department has committed Â£7 billion between 2015 and 2021 to deliver new school places, which is on top of investment in the free schools programme. The latest data shows that 825,000 additional places were created between May 2010 and May 2017, with many more delivered since then and in the pipeline. The Department is on track to create 1 million new school places this decade, the largest increase in school capacity in two generations.</p><p>Local authorities are responsible for arranging suitable full-time education for permanently excluded pupils, and for other pupils who (because of illness or other reasons) would not receive suitable education without such provision.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086774/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-15T09:28:35.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086774/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086774/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086774/answer/previousversion/107710","Biography information for Nick Gibb","60","Education","Education","2019-03-11","Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps he is taking to ensure that (a) more parents are able to access a place at their preferred school and (b) permanently excluded children are able to access places at alternative mainstream schools.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","230923"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086775","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-03-14","<p>The Government recognises that the causes of youth crime are complex and are often tied to local factors. Local authorities allocate funding and deliver youth services in line with local need. The Government has made over Â£200bn available to local authorities to spend on local services over this Spending Review.</p><p>The Government is committed to making sure young people have opportunities to develop their skills and benefit from youth services, which are an important partner in the strategy to tackle the root causes of serious violence.</p><p>My department will continue to work closely with the Home Office on the implementation of the Serious Violence Strategy.</p>","Eastleigh","Mims Davies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086775/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T14:45:52.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086775/answer","Biography information for Mims Davies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086775/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-03-11","Social Services: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of youth services and social services on reducing youth violence; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","230924"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086776","Department for International Trade","false","2019-03-14","<p>The Music Export Growth Scheme is designed to support the launch of UK music acts to international audiences through grants to UK-registered music businesses; principally independent record labels and music management companies.</p><p> </p><p>In the financial year to date - from 1 April 2018 to 28 February 2019 - the Music Export Growth Scheme has cost an estimated Â£766,000.</p><p> </p><p>The scheme is administered by the British Phonographic Industry (BPI).</p>","Beverley and Holderness","Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086776/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T16:26:27.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086776/answer","Biography information for Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086776/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-03-11","Music: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, pursuant to the Answer of 11 March 2019 to Question 229270 on Exports: Advertising, what estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of the Music Exporting Growth Scheme.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","230925"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086777","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-03-14","<p>The Government recognises that the causes of youth crime are complex and are often tied to local factors. Local authorities allocate funding and deliver youth services in line with local need. The Government has made over Â£200bn available to local authorities to spend on local services over this Spending Review.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to making sure young people have opportunities to develop their skills and benefit from youth services, which are an important partner in the strategy to tackle the root causes of serious violence. The Office for Civil Society (OCS), now based in DCMS, has spent over Â£667m on youth programmes and supporting youth service delivery between 2014/15 and 2017/18 - with Â£190m of that being spent in 2017/18.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, a new Â£200 million Youth Endowment Fund will be delivered over 10 years and will support interventions with children and young people at risk of involvement in crime and violence, will focus on those most at risk of youth violence including those displaying signs such as truancy, aggression and involvement in anti-social behaviour in order to steer them away from becoming serious offenders.</p><p> </p><p>My department will continue to work closely with the Home Office on the implementation of the Serious Violence Strategy.</p>","Eastleigh","Mims Davies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086777/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T17:15:57.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086777/answer","Biography information for Mims Davies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086777/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-03-11","Youth Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what plans his Department has to provide additional funding and support to youth services and projects engaging with young people at risk of violence.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","230926"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086778","Home Office","false","2019-03-14","<p>The Home Office collects and publishes data annually on the primary function of police officers, by Police Force Area, as part of the âPolice workforce, England and Walesâ statistical bulletins.</p><p>Functions data are collected under the Police Objective Analysis (POA) framework. Officers with multiple responsibilities are recorded under their primary function. The number and proportion of officers employed in frontline policing roles can be calculated according to the frontline policing model set out by Her Majestyâs Inspectorate of Constabulary and Fire &amp; Rescue Services (HMICFRS).</p><p>Data on the number and proportion of officers in frontline policing roles in Metropolitan and City of London Police forces, and in England and Wales, can be found in Table_F5 of the accompanying data tables:<br>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/728153/police-workforce-tabs-jul18.ods</p><p>Data at lower levels of geography are not held centrally.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086778/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T16:34:50.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086778/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086778/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-11","Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimates his Department has made of the reduction of frontline police officers in each year since 2015 in (a) Lambeth and Southwark BCU, (b) London and (c) England.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","230927"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086779","Home Office","false","2019-03-14","<p>The police funding settlement for 2019/20 increases overall funding for the police by around Â£970 million, including additional pensions funding and income from Council Tax. Following the announcement of the settlement, Police and Crime Commissioners have set out plans to recruit nearly 3,000 extra police officers.</p><p><br>The Chancellor of the Exchequer announced on 13 March an additional Â£100 million funding in 2019/20, including Â£80m of new funding from the Treasury. This will help in the policeâs immediate response to the rise in serious knife crime, enabling priority forces to immediately begin planning to put in place the additional capacity they need. The funding will also be invested in Violence Reduction Units, bringing together a range of agencies including health, education, social services and others, to develop a multi-agency approach in preventing serious violence altogether. It is important that we recognise that greater law enforcement on its own will not reduce serious violence and that we must continue to focus on prevention.</p><p>The majority of the investment will go towards supporting police forces where violent crime is impacting the most, to take immediate action to suppress the violence we are seeing, to make our streets safer. We are engaging with partners including the National Police Chiefsâ Council and the Association of Police and Crime Commissioners and we are developing the criteria by which forces will receive this funding.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086779/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T16:33:51.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086779/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086779/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-11","Crimes of Violence and Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans his Department has to (a) increase frontline police numbers and (b) ensure police have sufficient resources to tackle knife crime and other forms of violent crime.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","230928"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086780","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-03-14","<p>62 high rise student accommodation buildings which have Aluminium Composite Material (ACM) have been identified. 28 have completed remediation with 34 yet to be remediated. Of the 34 yet to remediated, 31 have either started remediation, have plans in place, or are developing plans. MHCLG officials continue to engage with local authorities, building owners and managing agents to ensure that student buildings with ACM cladding systems are remediated as swiftly as possible.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086780/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T14:17:44.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086780/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086780/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-03-11","Housing: Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what recent estimate he has made of the number of student residences which have been identified as having aluminium composite material cladding that is unlikely to meet the limited combustibility requirements set out in Building Regulations guidance; and what steps he is taking to ensure all student residences meet the requirements of that guidance.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","230845"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086781","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-03-19","<p>Universal Credit is now fully rolled out to all jobcentres as of December 2018. For the extremely small number of people who need to make a new claim to legacy benefits in Great Britain, the Department provides support through a dedicated DWP telephony line to assist with new claims to legacy benefits. Should a claimant require face-to-face contact, advice and support continues to be available in local Jobcentres to assist claimants to access their entitlements</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086781/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-19T10:00:35.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086781/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086781/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-03-11","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans she has in place for people to claim legacy benefits who have not been given access to universal credit in (a) full and (b) live service areas.","false","Biography information for Peter Grant","Glenrothes","Peter Grant","230846"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086782","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-03-14","<p>This is a devolved matter and the information provided relates to England only.</p><p> </p><p>Natural England runs a Species Recovery Programme which directly supports research and action to recover endangered or threatened species. Funding allocations for the Programme were Â£873,000, Â£737,000 and Â£777,000 in the years 2016/17, 2017/18 and 2018/19.</p><p> </p><p>This is only a small proportion of the Governmentâs expenditure on threatened species. Species conservation is integrated into funding programmes for protected sites, agri-environment schemes and wider investment in wildlife-rich habitats and ecosystems.</p><p> </p><p>Defraâs agencies and non-departmental bodies also work with a range of partners to support the recovery of threatened species. Natural England is working with a range of conservation organisations on the externally funded Back from the Brink programme to protect threatened species and their habitats. The Environment Agency is working with partners to support the conservation of freshwater priority species such as the freshwater pearl mussel and salmon.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr ThÃ©rÃ¨se Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086782/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T10:08:15.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086782/answer","Biography information for Dr ThÃ©rÃ¨se  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086782/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-03-11","Nature Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how much his Department has spent in restoring British endangered species in each if the last three years.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","230847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086783","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-03-14","<p>Information on the condition of National Nature Reserves is publicly available on Natural Englandâs designated sites viewer:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://designatedsites.naturalengland.org.uk/SearchEngland.aspx" target="_blank">https://designatedsites.naturalengland.org.uk/SearchEngland.aspx</a></p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr ThÃ©rÃ¨se Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086783/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T16:55:59.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086783/answer","Biography information for Dr ThÃ©rÃ¨se  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086783/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-03-11","Nature Reserves","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many national nature reserves are (a) at risk of deteriorating and (b) deteriorating.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","230848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086784","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-19","<p>NHS Resolution handles clinical negligence claims on behalf of National Health Service organisations and independent sector providers of NHS care in England. All claims received are categorised against pre-defined âcauseâ codes on its claims management system. The cause code refers to the main cause(s) of the incident in relation to the claim.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Resolution has advised that it is in the process of considering a new cause code for âNeonatalâ with a possible sub-code for Group B streptococcus. A decision on this is expected by summer 2019.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Resolution uses the codes to support the production of claims scorecards for NHS trusts which enables trusts to ascertain potential risks within their organisation and assess where local interventions are needed.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086784/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-19T16:19:28.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086784/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086784/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-11","Streptococcus","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he is taking to ensure NHS Resolution's claims management system has an injury code specific to invasive Group B Streptococcus (GBS) infection to improve the quality of data collection on GBS clinical negligence cases.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","230607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086785","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-03-14","<p>For the last five years, the percentage of licence applications Natural England has dealt with within 30 days, or to a different deadline agreed with the applicant, are as follows:</p><p> </p><p>2014/15: 55.80% of 11,520 applications dealt with on time</p><p>2015/16: 70.74% of 13,765 applications dealt with on time</p><p>2016/17: 88.13% of 15,122 applications dealt with on time</p><p>2017/18: 86.33% of 15,213 applications dealt with on time</p><p>2018/19 (to 11 March 2019): 88.38% of 15,025 applications dealt with on time</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr ThÃ©rÃ¨se Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086785/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T10:11:50.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086785/answer","Biography information for Dr ThÃ©rÃ¨se  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086785/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-03-11","Wildlife: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many wildlife licence applications Natural England has completed within the 30-day time frame in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","230849"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086786","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-03-14","<p>Natural England publishes figures on the number of enforcement actions it undertakes in its annual reports, which are publicly available and published on gov.uk.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/enforcement-laws-advice-on-protecting-the-natural-environment-in-england" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/enforcement-laws-advice-on-protecting-the-natural-environment-in-england</a></p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr ThÃ©rÃ¨se Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086786/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T16:50:38.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086786/answer","Biography information for Dr ThÃ©rÃ¨se  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086786/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-03-11","Sites of Special Scientific Interest","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many SSSI enforcement actions have Natural England undertaken in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","230850"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086787","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-19","<p>There are no plans to make Group B streptococcus infection a notifiable disease in England.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086787/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-19T16:39:21.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086787/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086787/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-11","Streptococcus","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if he will make invasive Group B Streptococcus infection a notifiable disease.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","230615"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086788","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-14","<p>The current Alternative Provider Medical Services provider has given notice to terminate their contracts. NHS Liverpool Clinical Commissioning Group is now working with primary care providers in Liverpool to identify an alternate provider or group of providers, that may include an existing General Medical Services contract holder, to run the affected services to ensure continuity for patients.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086788/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T16:59:56.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086788/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086788/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-11","General Practitioners: Garston and Halewood","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether he will enable Liverpool CCG to award General Medical Contracts rather than continue with Alternative Provider Medical Services Contracts to ensure the continuation of GP services currently being provided by Primary Care Connect in the Garston and Halewood Constituency.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","230660"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086789","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-03-20","<p>Whilst there is no direct, targeted funding planned in the current spending review to support the feasibility and development of marine energy projects, several wider cross cutting funding routes have been, and will continue to be, available to the sector.</p><p> </p><p>These include numerous previous phases of the Energy Entrepreneurs Fund and Innovate UKâs Smart Grant Fund, the latest round of which is open for proposals until 24<sup>th</sup> April.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086789/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-20T11:26:39.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086789/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086789/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-03-11","Tidal Power and Wave Power: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer to 11 March to Question 228713 on Nuclear Reactors, what direct funding is available for a feasibility and development project for (a) tidal and (b) wave energy projects.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","230851"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086790","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-14","<p>NHS Englandâs Primary Medical Care Policy and Guidance Manual (first published 15 November 2017) provides local commissioners of primary medical services the context, information and tools to safely commission and contract management primary medical care contracts.</p><p> </p><p>There is no prohibition on issuing General Medical Services or Personal Medical Services contracts under this guidance and every local commissioner needs to consider each individual case on the basis of local circumstances that apply. Considerations will also need to factor appropriate legislation and NHS Englandâs Standing Financial Instructions.</p><p> </p><p>Commissioners need to comply with their obligations under the Public Contract Regulations (âPCR 2015â) and the NHS (Procurement, Patient Choice and Competition Regulations) (No. 2) Regulations 2013 (âthe NHS Regulationsâ). One of the impacts of these Regulations is commissioner should not unnecessarily restrict contracts to only certain kinds of providers. In practice this will mean the use of Alternative Provider Medical Services contracts in procurements.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Englandâs Standing Financial Instructions additionally require all proposed clinical procurements for all types of revenue expenditure which last for five years or more, including options to extend clauses, must be submitted to and approved by the NHS England Commercial Executive Group before advertisement.</p><p> </p><p>Whilst these considerations do not the use of General and Personal Medical Services contracts where appropriate and justifiable, these are likely to be exceptional.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the NHS Long Term Plan, Parliament and the Government both asked the NHS to make consensus proposals for how primary legislation might be adjusted to better support delivery of the agreed changes set out in this plan.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086790/answer",,,,,"230662 ; 230663","2019-03-14T16:59:14.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086790/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086790/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-11","General Practitioners: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent assessment he has made of the effectiveness of his policy of not allowing GP services provided via Alternative Provider Medical Services Contracts to be provided using other contractual models such as General Medical Services Contracts; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","230661"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086791","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-03-15","<p>Of the up to Â£56m we announced in the Nuclear Sector Deal towards advanced nuclear technologies we have contractually committed to spend just under Â£10m on the Advanced Modular Reactor Programme. This includes contracts signed as part of the AMR Feasibility &amp; Development projects and the money provided to the Nuclear Regulators to increase their capability.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086791/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-15T12:08:39.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086791/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086791/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-03-11","Nuclear Reactors: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 11 March 2019 to Question 228711, what funding has been spent to date on the strategy for small modular nuclear reactors; and what funding has been contractually committed.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","230929"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086792","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-03-14","<p>On 27 August 2018, the Government announced that it will ban the use of hand-held remote controlled electronic collars (e-collars) for dogs. The ban will not include collars used for invisible fencing. The necessary legislation will be introduced as soon as Parliamentary time allows.</p><p> </p><p>The statutory codes of practice for the welfare of dogs and cats will be reviewed in the light of the change in the law on e-collars.</p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086792/answer",,,,,,"2019-03-14T11:40:30.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086792/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086792/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-03-11","Pets: Animal Welfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when he plans to bring forward legislative proposals to amend (a) the statutory Code of Practice for the Welfare of Dogs and Code of Practice for the Welfare of Cats in relation to invisible fencing containment systems and (b) the Animal Welfare Act 2006 to ban the use of hand-held remote controlled e-collar devices.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","230930"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1086793","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-14","<p>NHS Englandâs Primary Medical Care Policy and Guidance Manual (first published 15 November 2017) provides local commissioners of primary medical services the context, information and tools to safely commission and contract management primary medical care contracts.</p><p> </p><p>There is no prohibition on issuing General Medical Services or Personal Medical Services contracts under this guidance and every local commissioner needs to consider each individual case on the basis of local circumstances that apply. Considerations will also need to factor appropriate legislation and NHS Englandâs Standing Financial Instructions.</p><p> </p><p>Commissioners need to comply with their obligations under the Public Contract Regulations (âPCR 2015â) and the NHS (Procurement, Patient Choice and Competition Regulations) (No. 2) Regulations 2013 (âthe NHS Regulationsâ). One of the impacts of these Regulations is commissioner should not unnecessarily restrict contracts to only certain kinds of providers. In practice this will mean the use of Alternative Provider Medical Services contracts in procurements.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Englandâs Standing Financial Instructions additionally require all proposed clinical procurements for all types of revenue expenditure which last for five years or more, including options to extend clauses, must be submitted to and approved by the NHS England Commercial Executive Group before advertisement.</p><p> </p><p>Whilst these considerations do not the use of General and Personal Medical Services contracts where appropriate and justifiable, these are likely to be exceptional.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the NHS Long Term Plan, Parliament and the Government both asked the NHS to make consensus proposals for how primary legislation might be adjusted to better support delivery of the agreed changes set out in this plan.</p>","Winchester","St